summary: In the 17th century, people began creating machines like calculators to perform mathematical tasks.

text: William Schikers and God-Free Lebanese developed machine calculators and Charles Babbage designed early programmable machines including the analytical engine.
summary: These innovations laid the groundwork for modern computers by introducing concepts like punched cards for programming.

text: In the 19th century, Harmon Hallorith created tabular iterators for statistical tasks, leading to machines that could do more than just mathematical calculations.
summary: By the mid 20th century, powerful computers like any act emerged shifting the meaning of the world computer to machines rather than human calculators.
